The concept of isospin symmetry is most clearly established in so-called “mirror nuclei”, i.e., nuclei of the same mass, for which the number of protons and neutrons is exchanged, resulting in their structure being very similar. More generally, isobaric nuclei (with the same mass number A) have corresponding levels, which can be grouped into multiplets of states of common isospin. However, the isospin symmetry-breaking terms of the nuclear Hamiltonian should lead to each nuclear state having, in addition to its main component of isospin T, minor components of a different isospin. The amount of isospin mixing, as derived from experiment, can be understood as a measure of the magnitude of the symmetry violation. The breaking of the isospin symmetry by the Coulomb force increases with Z and for a given mass it is at its maximum for N=Z\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
