				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\gamma $$\end{document}-ray emission angle enabled by the superb position resolution of AGATA permits the development of a variety of novel experimental techniques, which take advantage of the Doppler effect to determine excited-state lifetimes. Such direct and model-independent lifetime measurements constitute an important complement to other experimental techniques.

At relativistic beam energies electromagnetic excitation occurs only as a one-step process due to the very short interaction time. Consequently, only low-spin states can be excited with reasonable cross section via the absorption of virtual photons of multipolarity E1, M1, E2, or E3. The cross section for the excitation of low-lying 2+\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
